    <prp:abstract>Long gamma-ray bursts (LGRBs), are the brightest transient events in the Universe. This, combined with their wide redshift range and their association with the collapse of massive, metal-poor stars, establishes LGRBs as powerful probes of cosmic star formation. However, the role of dust in the star formation history, chemical enrichment and evolution of these sources is currently still unclear, yet its importance cannot be overstated as it is directly related to the origin of the LGRB. Here we propose for 9.3 hours of band 7 ALMA observation of the host galaxy of GRB 031203, one of only 4 local (z&lt;0.1) GRBHs. Our aim is to pin down the shape of the IR SED and calculate robust values for the dust mass, dust temperature, total infrared luminosity and star-formation rate. Due to its unprecedented sensitivity, ALMA is the only current observatory that can detect GRBH 031203. Our proposed observation will allow us to carry out crucial comparisons between GRBH 031203 and GRBH 980425, the only other far-IR observed local GRBH. Our ultimate aim is to link the LGRB explosion to the conditions of the ISM as well as examine the role of dust in LGRB hosts harbouring metal poor, massive stars.</prp:abstract>
